Constructor chaining is the process where constructors call parent constructors sequentially.

```java
class A {
    A() { System.out.println("A"); }
}
class B extends A {
    B() { super(); System.out.println("B"); }
}
class C extends B {
    C() { super(); System.out.println("C"); }
}

// When C object created: Output → A, B, C
// Order: Object → A → B → C constructors execute
```

Diagram:
C() → super() → B() → super() → A() → Object()

```java
class Parent {
    int value = 10;
    void display() { System.out.println("Parent"); }
}

class Child extends Parent {
    int value = 20;

    void display() {
        System.out.println("Child");
    }

    void show() {
        System.out.println(this.value);   // 20 (current class)
        System.out.println(super.value);  // 10 (parent class)

        this.display();  // Child's display
        super.display(); // Parent's display
    }
}
```

**super** refers to parent class members
**this** refers to current class members

