```java
class A {
    private int valueA;

    // No default constructor
    A(int valueA) {
        this.valueA = valueA;
        System.out.println("A's parameterized constructor: valueA = " + valueA);
    }

    void display() {
        System.out.println("Value in A: " + valueA);
    }
}

class B extends A {
    private int valueB;

    // Must explicitly call super with parameter
    B(int valueA, int valueB) {
        super(valueA);  // MUST be first statement
        this.valueB = valueB;
        System.out.println("B's parameterized constructor: valueB = " + valueB);
    }

    // Overloaded constructor
    B(int valueB) {
        super(100);  // Providing default value for parent
        this.valueB = valueB;
        System.out.println("B's single-param constructor: valueB = " + valueB);
    }

    void display() {
        super.display();
        System.out.println("Value in B: " + valueB);
    }
}

class C extends B {
    private int valueC;

    C(int valueA, int valueB, int valueC) {
        super(valueA, valueB);  // Calls B's 2-param constructor
        this.valueC = valueC;
        System.out.println("C's constructor: valueC = " + valueC);
    }

    C(int valueC) {
        super(50);  // Calls B's single-param constructor
        this.valueC = valueC;
        System.out.println("C's single-param constructor: valueC = " + valueC);
    }

    @Override
    void display() {
        super.display();
        System.out.println("Value in C: " + valueC);
    }
}

public class ConstructorChainingDemo {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        System.out.println("=== Creating C with all parameters ===");
        C obj1 = new C(10, 20, 30);
        obj1.display();

        System.out.println("\n=== Creating C with single parameter ===");
        C obj2 = new C(99);
        obj2.display();

        // Constructor execution order:
        // For C(10,20,30): A(10) → B(10,20) → C(10,20,30)
        // For C(99): A(100) → B(50) → C(99)
    }
}
```

**Key Rules:**
1. super() must be first statement in constructor
2. If parent has no default constructor, child MUST call super with parameters
3. Constructor chain continues until Object class
4. this() and super() cannot coexist in same constructor

